---
import Slide from "../components/Slide.astro";
---

<Slide>
	<h2>From meaning to control</h2>
	<ul>
		<li class="fragment">A letter is a <strong>static pose</strong> — a swipe is a <strong>gesture over time</strong></li>
		<li class="fragment">Track landmark <em>trails</em>: palm position, pinch distance, hold duration</li>
		<li class="fragment">
			The unglamorous part is what makes it usable: <strong>state machines, velocity thresholds, cooldowns</strong>
		</li>
	</ul>
	<table class="mapping fragment">
		<tbody>
			<tr><td>🖐️ open palm, swipe left / right</td><td>next / previous slide</td></tr>
			<tr><td>🤏 pinch spread / close</td><td>zoom in / out</td></tr>
			<tr><td>✊ fist, hold</td><td>overview / escape</td></tr>
			<tr><td>🙌 two palms, hold</td><td>fullscreen*</td></tr>
			<tr><td>⌨️ <code>g</code></td><td>toggle gesture mode</td></tr>
		</tbody>
	</table>
	<p class="footnote fragment">* browsers may require a real key/click for fullscreen — <code>f</code> always works</p>
	<aside class="notes">
		One physical motion must fire exactly one command: after each command there's a ~900ms cooldown and all trails
		reset. Without that, a single swipe fires three "next"s. Keyboard stays active the whole time — gesture mode is
		additive, never a trap.
	</aside>
</Slide>

<style>
	ul {
		font-size: 0.7em;
		text-align: left;
	}
	.mapping {
		margin: 0.6em auto 0;
		font-size: 0.55em;

		td {
			padding: 0.15em 0.8em;
			text-align: left;
			border-bottom: 1px solid #1e293b;
		}

		td:last-child {
			color: #4ade80;
		}
	}
	.footnote {
		font-size: 0.4em;
		color: #64748b;
	}
</style>
